  "nursesNote": "Family therapy treats the family as a system, viewing a member's problem in the context of how the family functions. Goals include improving communication, clarifying roles, resolving conflict, and setting healthy boundaries. The nurse or therapist stays neutral, does not take sides, and encourages every member to speak so patterns become clear. Unhealthy patterns include enmeshment (over-involvement with blurred boundaries), disengagement (too much distance), scapegoating (blaming one member for the family's problems), and triangulation (pulling in a third person to avoid direct conflict). Families often resist change (homeostasis), which is expected. The nurse supports open, respectful communication and healthier roles and boundaries.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Treat the family as a unit/system",
    "Stay neutral and avoid taking sides",
    "Encourage all members to participate",
    "Identify unhealthy patterns like scapegoating and triangulation",
    "Promote healthy communication and boundaries"
  ],
